[http://www.flickr.com/photos/dolspics] [http://www.flickr.com/photos/beachcomberaustralia] In 1934 the premises was occupied by Peerless Manufacturing Co. Ltd.. One of their products, the &quot;Quicka Nitta&quot;, claimed to be a magical device that would cut knitting time in half, &quot;made by the magic new process of plastic moulding.&quot;

See the <i>The Australian Women's Weekly</i>, p. 23 for the advertisement, and p. 24 for the article - <a href="http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/printIssue/196097" rel="nofollow">trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/printIssue/196097</a> [PDF download, 13 MB)

Peerless Manufacturing Co. Ltd., manufacturers and merchants, registered their company in Sydney in Sept. 1932, with a capital of £1000.  - <a href="http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/16891100" rel="nofollow">trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/16891100</a>
